\f1\fs22 \cf2 \cb3 \CocoaLigature0  You are a senior product architect and full-stack engineer.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 I am building a platform called Bassline. It originally started as a Pilates tracking app but I want to expand it to support youth athlete welfare by coordinating training load across \cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 multiple coaches and recovery practitioners.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 The goal is to prevent overtraining and improve recovery by giving visibility of a child's full training schedule across clubs, schools, and recovery sessions.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 The system should be athlete-centric.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 CORE USER TYPES\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Users in the system include:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Coach (GAA, rugby, soccer etc.)\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Parent / guardian\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Pilates instructor (recovery specialist)\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Athlete (child)\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Standard user (adult Pilates user not involved in youth sport)\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Admin\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Important design rule:\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 A user can have multiple roles (for example a coach could also be an athlete).\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 TEAM CREATION MODEL\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 We are using the following onboarding flow:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 1. Coach creates a team\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 2. Coach adds athletes to the team roster\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 3. Parents receive an invite to claim the athlete profile\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 4. Parent confirms the athlete profile and grants permissions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 5. Parent can optionally add:\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3    \'95 additional coaches\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3    \'95 Pilates instructors\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3    \'95 other practitioners\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 The athlete profile becomes the central object in the system.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 ATHLETE PROFILE\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Each athlete profile should contain:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 name\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 age\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 sports played\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 teams\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 injury history (optional future feature)\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 training sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 recovery sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Multiple coaches or practitioners may be linked to a single athlete.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 RELATIONSHIP MODEL\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Users interact with athlete profiles through relationships.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Example relationship types:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 coach\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 pilates_instructor\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 parent\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 guardian\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 physio\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 These relationships control permissions and UI views.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 TRAINING SESSION TYPES\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Coaches must be able to log:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 team training sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 matches\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 conditioning sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 skill sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Session fields should include:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 date\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 duration\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 intensity (low / medium / high OR RPE scale)\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 sport\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 session type\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 team\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Pilates instructors must be able to log:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 recovery sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 mobility work\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 injury prevention sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 muscle imbalance corrective work\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 CORE FEATURES\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 1. TEAM MANAGEMENT\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Coaches should be able to:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 create teams\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 manage rosters\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 log team training sessions once and apply them to all athletes\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 view athlete training load summaries\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 2. ATHLETE TIMELINE\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Each athlete should have a timeline view showing:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 training sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 matches\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Pilates sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 recovery sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 The UI should resemble a Notion-style timeline.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 3. TRAINING LOAD ANALYTICS\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 The system should calculate weekly training load.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Example method:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Training Load = Session RPE \'d7 Duration\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Display:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 weekly load\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 intensity distribution\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 warnings for excessive load\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Example warning:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 "High intensity sessions exceeded recommended weekly limit."\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 4. USER INTERFACES\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Design interfaces for:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Coach Hub\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 team management\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 session logging\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 athlete load summary\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Pilates Instructor Hub\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 recovery session builder\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 corrective exercise assignments\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 athlete recovery tracking\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Parent Dashboard\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 athlete training overview\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 timeline\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 permission management\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Athlete View\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 personal timeline\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Pilates sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 recovery schedule\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Standard Pilates User\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 simple Pilates workout tracking\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 no sports features\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Admin\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 full system visibility\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 PERMISSIONS\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Parents control access to their child's athlete profile.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Parents can:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 approve coaches\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 approve Pilates instructors\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 revoke access\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Coaches should only see athletes linked to their team.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Pilates instructors should only see athletes they are assigned to.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 DATA MODEL TASK\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Design a database schema including:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Users\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Teams\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 AthleteProfiles\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Relationships\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 TeamMemberships\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Permissions\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Include table structures and key relationships.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 ARCHITECTURE TASK\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Recommend a scalable architecture for this feature including:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 backend services\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 API structure\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 database design\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 role/permission system\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 UI TASK\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Suggest UI layouts for:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Coach hub\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Athlete timeline\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Pilates instructor hub\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 Parent dashboard\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 SAFETY / GDPR TASK\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Identify GDPR considerations for child data including:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 parental consent\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 data minimisation\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 role-based access\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \'95 audit logs\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 OUTPUT FORMAT\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Provide:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 1. System architecture overview\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 2. Database schema\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 3. Role and permission model\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 4. Key API endpoints\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 5. UI structure recommendations\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 6. Future expansion ideas\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 IMPORTANT UX CONSTRAINT\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 --------------------------------\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Bassline already has an existing Pilates user experience.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Standard users currently use the platform only for Pilates workouts and progress tracking.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 This UX MUST remain unchanged.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 The new youth sport functionality must be implemented as an optional extension layer.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Rules:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 1. Standard Pilates users should not see any sports or coaching features.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 2. Sports functionality should only appear when:\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3    - a coach creates a team\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3    - a parent claims an athlete profile\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3    - a Pilates instructor is linked to an athlete\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3    - a user joins a team\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 3. The existing Pilates workflow should remain:\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Dashboard\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Pilates Sessions\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Workout Tracking\cf4 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Progress\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 4. Athlete and team features should appear as additional navigation items only when relevant.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 This design principle is called progressive disclosure.\cf4 \cb1 \
\
\cf2 \cb3 Please ensure that the system architecture and UI structure maintain this constraint. \cf4 \cb1 \
\
\
